here!’’ I said, ‘‘Who's she talking to?’’

1505
01:47:37,150 --> 01:47:40,745
And I said, ‘‘She's being pursued
by invisible enemies.’’

1506
01:47:43,323 --> 01:47:45,188
Who does she think they are?

1507
01:47:45,258 --> 01:47:49,752
I don't know exactly.
It's hard to tell.

1508
01:47:49,830 --> 01:47:53,231
Charles?
Fix that curtain in the hallway.

1509
01:47:57,737 --> 01:48:00,137
The curtain in the hallway?

1510
01:48:26,299 --> 01:48:29,029
Come here. Come here.

1511
01:48:31,605 --> 01:48:34,506
Let me see that, please.

1512
01:48:39,079 --> 01:48:41,070
Let me show you the painter.

1513
01:48:42,249 --> 01:48:44,308
I did that one and that one.

1514
01:48:44,384 --> 01:48:47,945
- That one's good.
- Let me show you what one it is.

1515
01:48:53,960 --> 01:48:56,121
This is my character.

1516
01:48:56,196 --> 01:48:58,994
That's your character?

1517
01:48:59,065 --> 01:49:02,660
- What are biscuit teeth?
- Her dog!

1518
01:49:02,736 --> 01:49:05,933
- Biscuit Teeth.
- That's her dog?

1519
01:49:07,407 --> 01:49:10,899
Leave it the way it is.
Gimme a break.

1520
01:49:10,977 --> 01:49:13,878
Isn't that better? Look.

1521
01:49:13,947 --> 01:49:15,380
Much better.

1522
01:49:16,917 --> 01:49:21,513
Everything has to be black and white.
Everything has to be old-fashioned.

1523
01:49:21,588 --> 01:49:24,523
It just looks better like that.

1524
01:49:24,591 --> 01:49:27,924
The old man, I think, took off
pretty much for good...

1525
01:49:27,994 --> 01:49:32,260
when I was probably
five or six years old I guess.

1526
01:49:32,332 --> 01:49:35,199
I can't remember
that period of time very well.

1527
01:49:35,268 --> 01:49:37,930
But I didn't see him
too regularly after that.

1528
01:49:38,004 --> 01:49:41,565
He was over here for the most part:
Madison, Dixon.

1529
01:49:41,641 --> 01:49:43,700
Kind of gone most of the time.

1530
01:49:43,777 --> 01:49:48,077
I think he has sort of
a hard time emotionally.

1531
01:49:49,649 --> 01:49:53,745
Sometimes I'll feel like I want
to express affection to the old man.

1532
01:49:53,820 --> 01:49:57,153
I feel like I want to put my arm
around him or shake his hand...

1533
01:49:57,223 --> 01:49:59,214
or get close in some way.

1534
01:49:59,292 --> 01:50:02,125
He can't do it.

1535
01:50:06,199 --> 01:50:10,397
- How tight?
- Pretty tight.

1536
01:50:10,470 --> 01:50:13,439
What a disaster this is,
taking these records out.

1537
01:50:13,506 --> 01:50:16,475
I was planning to live here
until I died!

1538
01:50:16,543 --> 01:50:20,809
I didn't want to move out of this place,
and move all these damn records.

1539
01:50:21,948 --> 01:50:23,882
That'll teach you to have a hobby.

1540
01:50:23,950 --> 01:50:29,013
Be careful with those.
You break them, I'll kill you.

1541
01:50:29,089 --> 01:50:31,853
My copy of Frank Bunch
and His Fuzzy Wuzzies.

1542
01:50:34,294 --> 01:50:36,888
Put those there on that futon.

1543
01:50:38,264 --> 01:50:41,756
Tight as you can.
Pull it out and I'll cut it.

1544
01:50:41,835 --> 01:50:44,167
Jesus, that wife of mine.

1545
01:50:44,237 --> 01:50:47,365
Having me move to France,
for God's sake.

1546
01:50:48,608 --> 01:50:51,577
It's too late now.
The die is cast.

1547
01:52:33,113 --> 01:52:35,775
A lot of stuff is in here
and some of it's in there.

1548
01:52:35,849 --> 01:52:39,080
Pulling up to here would be
the best thing. I don't know.

1549
01:52:39,152 --> 01:52:43,714
We'll have to look.
We have plywood we can put down.

1550
01:52:43,790 --> 01:52:47,624
She's having a ball out there,
telling those guys what to do.

1551
01:52:51,898 --> 01:52:55,994
God, giant trucks are here,
everything.

1552
01:52:56,069 --> 01:52:57,502
Embarrassing.

1553
01:53:04,744 --> 01:53:08,908
You think those guys are going to be
sensitive to my record collection?

1554
01:53:09,983 --> 01:53:11,974
Bunch of football jocks.

1555
01:53:12,051 --> 01:53:16,044
‘‘Whaddya got here? A bunch
of old albums or somethin'?’’

1556
01:53:20,360 --> 01:53:22,590
Is there anything you're going to miss
about this country?

1557
01:53:22,662 --> 01:53:26,325
A certain relaxed quality that people
have here that Europeans don't have.

1558
01:53:26,399 --> 01:53:28,196
They're more formal.

1559
01:53:28,268 --> 01:53:30,532
America's a big ‘‘slobville’’?

1560
01:53:30,603 --> 01:53:34,539
I went to get my friend’s belongings
in Eureka.

1561
01:53:34,607 --> 01:53:37,508
It was at these people's house.
I went into their living room.

1562
01:53:37,577 --> 01:53:41,809
They had this chair that was
a gold plastic football helmet...

1563
01:53:41,881 --> 01:53:44,406
with a red and blue padded seat.

1564
01:53:44,484 --> 01:53:49,581
They had double-wide couches and
a four-foot TV screen with Nintendo.

1565
01:53:49,656 --> 01:53:51,590
A Ninja Turtle game was on.

1566
01:53:51,658 --> 01:53:55,617
A giant, fat teenager
was sitting there, mesmerized.

1567
01:53:55,695 --> 01:53:57,629
You don't see
too much of that in France.

1568
01:53:59,399 --> 01:54:02,926
How do you feel
about leaving your family here?

1569
01:54:03,002 --> 01:54:06,301
I don't have any feelings about it
one way or the other.

1570
01:54:06,372 --> 01:54:07,862
What do I care?

1571
01:54:07,941 --> 01:54:11,741
Never see that mother or brother anyway.
Talks to them like once a year.

1572
01:54:11,811 --> 01:54:14,609
What about Jesse?

1573
01:54:14,681 --> 01:54:17,081
He's devastated that we're leaving.

1574
01:54:17,150 --> 01:54:19,778
On the other hand, we told him
he could come and stay with us there.

1575
01:54:19,853 --> 01:54:23,949
He's thrilled about that.
We gave him $500 for plane fare...

1576
01:54:24,023 --> 01:54:26,253
so he's going to come.

1577
01:54:26,326 --> 01:54:30,626
- How about Max?
- Max I feel bad about.

1578
01:54:30,697 --> 01:54:34,155
He doesn't have too many other people
to talk to.

1579
01:54:34,234 --> 01:54:37,726
I'm probably his closest
human relationship in the world.

1580
01:54:42,141 --> 01:54:44,609
These are all records?

1581
01:54:44,677 --> 01:54:46,975
Those 78s you were talking about?

1582
01:54:47,046 --> 01:54:48,479
Yep.

1583
01:54:51,751 --> 01:54:54,743
So I've got no patience
for Hollywood bullshit.

1584
01:54:56,222 --> 01:54:59,817
I can't think in those terms.

1585
01:54:59,893 --> 01:55:04,296
I've already got so much of my life
wasted with those people down there.

1586
01:55:04,364 --> 01:55:08,300
Animation? Forget it. No.
I'm not interested in it at all.

1587
01:55:08,368 --> 01:55:12,464
There hasn't been a decent animated film
made in this country since 1940.

1588
01:55:12,538 --> 01:55:15,735
‘‘Cheery Pop Tart’’ is an abomination.

1589
01:55:15,808 --> 01:55:18,834
Larry Wells is an idiot.
It's going to be a piece of garbage.

1590
01:55:18,912 --> 01:55:21,710
I'm not interested.
All right.

1591
01:55:21,781 --> 01:55:23,214
So long.

1592
01:55:28,121 --> 01:55:32,421
I was on a conference call with Charles
Webb, a friend of Dan O'Neill's.

1593
01:55:32,492 --> 01:55:35,950
They're putting together
the ‘‘Cherry Pop Tart’’ film.

1594
01:55:36,029 --> 01:55:38,463
They got on the phone with
some guy in L.A. who says...

1595
01:55:38,531 --> 01:55:42,797
‘‘Hey! I'm your kind of guy.
Remember 'Tommy Toilet'? I love it!’’

1596
01:55:47,307 --> 01:55:49,468
They want to make a movie?

1597
01:55:49,542 --> 01:55:54,912
The natural film, of course.
It's a ‘‘go’’ project.

1598
01:55:56,983 --> 01:56:01,386
This is how I felt
after that last hell week...

1599
01:56:01,454 --> 01:56:04,150
of you filming me here.

1600
01:56:04,223 --> 01:56:07,818
‘‘How perfectly goddamned delightful
it all is, to be sure.’’

1601
01:56:07,894 --> 01:56:11,159
When I was a kid, if I ever started
showing enthusiasm for anything...

1602
01:56:11,230 --> 01:56:13,164
by brother Charles would say...

1603
01:56:13,232 --> 01:56:16,668
‘‘How perfectly goddamned delightful
it all is, to be sure.’’

1604
01:56:16,736 --> 01:56:19,569
Always take the wind
out of my sails.

1605
01:56:19,639 --> 01:56:22,267
Even though I don't see him often,
whenever I'm with him...

1606
01:56:22,342 --> 01:56:26,244
it revives that keen awareness
of that...

1607
01:56:26,312 --> 01:56:31,375
of being very removed
or extremely separated...

1608
01:56:31,451 --> 01:56:33,715
from the rest of humanity
and the world in general.

1609
01:56:33,786 --> 01:56:36,687
I kinda like that feeling.

1610
01:56:36,756 --> 01:56:40,317
‘‘How perfectly goddamned delightful
it all is, to be sure.’’

1611
01:57:14,060 --> 01:57:17,826
Fix it, Charles. Put back the towel
the way I had it.

1612
01:57:17,897 --> 01:57:19,831
First put the towel up.

1613
01:57:21,801 --> 01:57:24,463
Watch you don't pull the shade
all the way off the thing.

1614
01:57:24,537 --> 01:57:25,970
I won't.

1615
01:57:28,808 --> 01:57:32,244
Can't come in and disrupt
people's house like this!

1616
01:57:32,311 --> 01:57:33,471
Where are the babies?

1617
01:57:33,546 --> 01:57:35,878
I don't know. I think
that little girl is in my room.

